**Other Input Example:**

Here, **n** means size of the vector(given input). And we have make n/2 pairs.

- Input = [5,11,9,1], n=4
- Then we have to group them into n/2 pairs. 
- The Possible pairs are: (1,9), (1,11), (1,5), (9,11), (11,5), (5,9).
- Now we want to find the maximum sum of any n/2 pairs. And, sum from one pair need to taken as min of those numbers.

Possible output sums are shown below:

min(1,9) = 1, min(5,11) = 5     So, sum = 6(1+5)
min(1,11) = 1, min(9,5) = 5     So, sum = 6(1+5)
min(1,5) = 1,  min(11,9) = 9    So, sum = 10(1+9)   // Output

Now, we have to return the maximum sum of any n/2 pairs.
Thus, output = 10 would give us the maximum sum of min of n/2 pairs.

Hope, it helps.    Happy Coding  :)

**Given Basic Test-case Example:**

Input = [1,2,3,4],  n =4
Then we have to group them into n/2 pairs. possible pairs are: (1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4), (3,4) . 
Possible output sums are shown below:
( min(1,4) = 1 + min(2,3) = 2 ) = 3
( min(1,3) = 1 + min(2,4) = 2 ) = 3
( min(1,2) = 1 + min(3,4) = 3 ) = 4 // Output

Thus, output = 4 would give us the maximum sum of min pairs.

**Solution:**
```
class Solution
{
public:
    int arrayPairSum(vector<int> &nums)
    {
        sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
        int sum = 0, count = 0;
        for (int i = nums.size() - 1; i >= 0; i -= 2)
            if (count != nums.size() / 2)
            {
                sum += min(nums[i], nums[i - 1]);
                count++;
            }
        return sum;
    }
};
```
